stylometry: Aggregate planning is the model in which you use to measure workforce levels and production schedules.  It allows you to see the different levels of workers and their rate of work and lets you put a schedule together which maxmizes or minimizes the amount of work you need to do at a specific plant (or any variation just an example).  In aggregate planning you need to consider that the workforce level is different for every person and you can just take one person you need to take a sample of many different employees in order to come up with some sort of average.  The goal of aggregate planning is to use the least amount of workers to produces the amount of products you need to produce in the shortest amount of time.  There are tradeoffs involved.  If you try and produce a product very fast you might need to use a more skilled worker which is going to cost you more money.  If you need to cut down costs and use fewer employees your production schedules might be a little longer because you do not have the amount of workers needed to minimize the amount of time it takes to make a product in your factory.
